##These famous nurses fought with their lives in Wuhan

I-CAIJING

CAIJING magazine official Wechat. "CAIJING" magazine, sponsored by the China Securities Market Research Center, was first published in 1998, adhering to the news concept of "independence, exclusiveness and originality" , and is known for authoritative, impartial and professional reporting, it is a must-read publication for policy-makers, researchers and managers in the field of politics and economics.

Especially in the initial panic stage, the majority of the female group of front-line nurses stood in the front, to meet the wind and rain, prop up the initial hope

By Chen Liang, CAIJING correspondent

Editor | Sheryl Rong

It's International Women's Day again, and for all Chinese women, especially the one million who have been staking out Wuhan, the epicenter of the epidemic, this year is decidedly grim. Some are still fighting in the most dangerous front, some have been fragrant eliminate jade meteorite, some are still suffering from the virus.

After more than a month of life and death struggle, China's fight against the new crown epidemic has come to a critical moment. As at 2400 hours on March 7,2020,103 new cases had been confirmed nationwide on the same day, 74 new cases had been confirmed in Wuhan, and the number of new cases confirmed in one day had finally dropped to double digits. But from the national point of view, as of March 8 at 15:00, the country reported a total of 80,859 confirmed cases, a total of 3,100 deaths, a total of 57,172 cured discharged from hospital, the losses and injuries caused by the epidemic is unprecedented, the progress of fighting the epidemic is also unprecedented.

Now, the spread of the epidemic across China has been initially controlled, which is the result of joint efforts, especially the efforts of the thousands of health care workers in the front line. Not just the tens of thousands of medical workers left behind in Wuhan, but 40,000 medical rescue teams from across the country. Their stories of struggle to save lives have touched and inspired hundreds of millions of people inside and outside the affected areas, and it is the larger numbers of health care workers, the vast majority of them women, who are fighting alongside frontline doctors.

"The medical team is a team that is easily overlooked, and our sisters are as important as our doctors are, " Zhang Wenhong, head of the Shanghai medical care expert team and director of the infection department at Mount Hua Hospital, said in a recent interview with the media, everyone is eulogizing the doctor, but this is not enough, the more complete statement should be the medical staff, as well as the general public, we are all working together.

From the beginning of the year to the last two months, tens of thousands of newly crowned patients have been accompanied by tens of thousands of sisters, nurses, who not only care for the illness, but also pay attention to the patients'life needs and psychological comfort.

By March 8, during the reporting process of three female reporters from Caijing who had held fast to the epidemic area in Wuhan for 38 days, they had interviewed a number of nurses who had held fast to the front line of fighting against the epidemic, and listened to their experiences in fighting the epidemic, they also talk about their personal experiences and joys and sorrows, which are poignant, warm, tense, expectant and confident.

1. Summer Snow, community nurse: diagnosed, treated, rehired

Xia Xue (not her real name) , a nurse at a Community Health Service Center in Kong Hon, said, "I moved a dozen oxygen tanks one step at a time that day. I hated myself for being so weak. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On February 16, Summer Snow (third from the right) was discharged from the Wuhan Red Cross Hospital, where he was placed under 14-day isolation

Summer Snow waits for the results of the final nucleic acid test on March 7. She had done it four times before. Once positive, she was admitted to the isolation ward of Wuhan Red Cross Hospital. Two negative results. She was discharged, quarantined for 14 days. If the last two tests are negative, she'll be back in the running. Summer Snow is a nurse at a Neighborhood Community Health Service Center in the Kong Hon District of Wuhan. But now her front line is at the Wuhan Red Cross Hospital, where she works as a nurse in a fever isolation ward, caring for inpatients infected with the new coronavirus.

It all goes back 46 days. At 10 a.m. on Jan. 21, Summer Snow, who was on a home rotation, received a call from the head nurse, asking if she could come to the Wuhan Red Cross Hospital for support. Without thinking, she agreed. "We have our own responsibility. We go where we are sent. ". By then, news of a human-to-human transmission of the new coronavirus had been circulating. "I think I know what I'm going to do, " she said, as she lowered the phone. Summer Snow said the Red Cross Hospital must be short-staffed because of the new pneumonia in Wuhan.

At 3 p.m. on Jan. 22, she attended a training session with other doctors who came to her aid to educate her about the disease and how to prevent it. It was a strange day at the Red Cross Hospital in front of Summer Snow. The emergency room was packed, the doctors were surrounded by patients, and there was a line at the door. She had never seen anything like it, not even during flu season. There were warning signs, Summer Snow recalled. At the Community Health Center, which began in late November, patients with flu like symptoms were still feverish and cold after a dozen days of routine fluids. When we got to the Red Cross Hospital, we found it was still the same. She wondered if her former patients at the health center had been infected with the virus.

On January 23rd, the city of Wuhan was sealed off, the first day Summer Snow officially entered the Red Cross. She is a nurse in the fever ward on the fourth floor, which has more than 60 beds. Her memory was not tied to the siege, but was laid out in front of her, the first time she saw and put on a protective suit. Under the guidance of the teacher, it is not difficult to put the protective clothing on the body, put on a mask, eye mask, lock the protective clothing, until they cover themselves inside and outside, for a moment, the feeling of oxygen deprivation diffuse. Summer Snow gasped, but he couldn't inhale, and his chest felt like a heavy stone.

Unable to adjust, she slumped in her chair. A few minutes later, his forehead was drenched in sweat. Even so, there were moments of the day when she dreaded it: She was sweating so much that her mask slipped down her ear; her glove suddenly broke. "There's a feeling of being caught off guard, " Summer Snow said.

So everyday protection became a habit. Even back at the hospital's segregated hotel, where they shared a room, she and her roommate wore masks to chat or relax. "It has become a conscious act of us, " says Summer Snow, both to protect ourselves from infecting others.

Basic care includes temperature, pulse, and oxygen saturation, plus fluids and dressing change. It rings nonstop in the ward. In addition to the regular work, because of the limited manpower, other jobs have to be temporarily filled. Most of the patients in Summer Snow's ward needed oxygen, sometimes from a tube. On one occasion, she carried a dozen oxygen tanks back and forth alone, replacing the empty tanks next to the patients with full ones. She gripped the steel-cast oxygen tank with her hand and, step by step, attached it to the trolley. Pushing a 100-pound oxygen tank to the patient's side. Looking back on her days in the ward, it was the most difficult one she could remember. She scolded herself for not being strong enough to move about for at least ten minutes at a time.

In February, the hospital ordered a CT scan of every department, and those days, Summer Snow had a sore throat, worried that he would be "hit, " while reassuring himself that he wouldn't, "usually often run, also did not have how cold, immunity is still good" . It turns out she has an infection in her lower left lung, which we need to confirm. On February 2nd, the nucleic acid test was positive. Unable to continue working, Summer Snow became a patient on the tenth floor of the Red Cross Ward. From Ward nurses to patients, she was somewhat frustrated, "sometimes I don't think I should get sick, otherwise I can help more people, now I have to ask others to help me. ".

So all she had to do was get better and get out of the hospital. Summer Snow browsed the Internet for information about the new pneumonia, adjusted her mood, and told herself to eat, even if she couldn't. Eleven days later, she was discharged. On this point, she is quite a little proud, "I was hospitalized really short, the next bed 16 days after discharge. ".

Seeing the results of the last nucleic acid test coming out, Summer Snow couldn't help himself and a few days ago asked his boss, my illness is gone, where do I need to go?

2. Wang Kunyu, head nurse of the Outpatient Department: He was scolded and cried by the patient, but he could not stay idle

Wang Kunyu, head nurse of the fever clinic of Tianyou Hospital affiliated to Wuhan University of Science and Technology, said, "those who think the stars are very bright don't see the nurses' eyes. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Patients poured in like a tide. The fever clinic of Tianyou Hospital affiliated to Wuhan University of Science and Technology began to work 24 hours a day. In general, the Infectious Disease Clinic only works during the daytime. To this end, the hospital has deployed doctors and nurses from all departments to strengthen the strength of fever clinic.

On January 22, the head nurse of the call center, Wang Kunyu, received a phone call from the director of the Nursing Department. Because before she was in charge of fever triage in the call center, the outpatient hall is the First Line of Defense, triage, all patients into the hall to take temperature, counseling. Wang Kunyu realized the severity was beyond imagination, "It may not feel like something we talked about before, like the flu or some other infectious disease, so when I got the call from the chief, I wasn't surprised, it was expected, it was the trust of the hospital. ".

Born in the 1980s, she became the youngest head nurse at 24, and Wang is confident in her immunity. Even though she knew it was a very contagious new virus, she was not afraid, and the fever clinic more than 40 nurses encouraged each other, from the Spring Festival until now.

When she arrived at the fever clinic, she basically worked around the clock for more than ten hours every day. Wang Kunyu had never had a rest. The hospital could not bear to see her anymore. She was forced to take a day off. Even at home, all kinds of phone calls kept going. She needed to deal with all kinds of things.

On January 29, Tianyou hospital became a designated hospital, but the transformation was not completely completed, so patients could only be admitted while undergoing the transformation. A large number of patients were concentrated in the fever clinic, but the families and patients could not understand. Wang Kunyu remembers one day, the family members carried the patient in and put him on the ground, and then left him there, blocking the others from going to the doctor. The family members also began to make noise. "No matter how hard I tried, some of my colleagues and I found a hospital bed and carried the patient up to the observation room, " Wang recalled.

After a patient arrives at the hospital, he first goes to the fever clinic. The first step is pre-examination and triage, and the second step is registration. Because the state has to collect detailed information about patients'visits to various hospitals, registration information is also very important. The third step is registration, and then wait for the doctor to see you. The first three steps are all done by an outpatient nurse.

As head nurse, you have to coordinate procedures, arrange personnel, and deal with emergencies. There were so many emergencies every day, and some patients were so anxious, and their families were so excited, that their request was as simple as to be hospitalized, to be treated effectively. "But there was really no way to solve it, and my friends and relatives came to me, but I couldn't, " Wang said.

Wang Kunyu had to take on the responsibility of regulating the emotions of the patients and their families, "I'm a fireman, " she said, "and often there are family members who get emotional and start kicking the table and sitting on the chair. " All she can do is explain, communicate, listen, comfort, and tell them what to do next, explain what Wuhan is doing and how they can be helped.

At times, these comforts are no more than a bed. On February 3, Wang Kunyu cried because the patient scolded her. "She was a good person, " said her colleague. "The patient put all the pressure on her. "

At that time, Wang Kunyu felt all kinds of emotional ups and downs, some family members will be very fierce, once the problem of hospitalization, immediately change their attitude, to the medical staff thousands of thanks.

It was her colleagues who moved her. Some of the nurses may seem ordinary, but at this particular time, the work ethic is high, especially for older nurses. One of the nurses will retire in a few months (the retiring age of the nurses is 55) , "I told the leaders not to let her go to work at that age, but they kept going. Tang Yan, a 50-year-old nurse in general practice, has been working in the fever clinic since day 1, with only a half-hour break for lunch between 8 a.m. and 6 p.m. , and she still insists on attending the fever clinic today.

Zhang Xinping, a nurse who retired two years ago, has a daughter who works as a lawyer in Beijing and comes from a good family. Her daughter called her and said, "don't go to work, you can take leave, if you have to resign, I support you, you don't care about the pension. ". "your mother worked her whole life, " she replied. "It would be a shame to run off like that. "

"those who think the stars are very bright do not see the eyes of the nurses. " This is a very popular video with shaking sound. When Wang Kunyu and her colleagues saw the video, they were very moved, "It's like you've done something and there are a lot of people who will understand and support you. "

Wang's team of nurses is older on average, about 45, but they have all agreed to hold out until the epidemic is over. "I couldn't stay idle, and then I wanted to go to the rehabilitation center to continue my work, " Wang said.

From Shanghai to Wuhan, I can't remember the last few days

Wang Huijuan, head nurse of the Department of Critical Care Medicine at Mount Hua Hospital affiliated to Fudan University, Supports Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital: "The most comfortable moment of every day is the moment when the protective clothing is removed. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Today is the 45th day of her visit to Wuhan's Golden Lake Hospital. Wang Huijuan doesn't remember the day of her visit to Wuhan. She just knows that today is another working day.

On January 23, after Ma Xin, deputy director of the Mount Hua Hospital, issued the notice on sending medical teams to help Hubei cope with the epidemic of COVID-19 pneumonia, Wang Huijuan and other key forces immediately signed up to participate, at the same time, he checked the option responsible for the critically ill patients on the expression of interest.

After signing up, Wang Huijuan told the news to her husband, in order not to affect the mood of more family members, she decided to tell parents, children after eating New Year's Eve dinner. But the announcement couldn't wait until after dinner. At 5:00 p.m. on New Year's Eve, Wang Huijuan and her family were wrapping spring rolls. The notice came. The first batch of 135 medical team members from Shanghai to Hubei needed to leave immediately. She could not eat the New Year's Eve dinner in time.

Putting down her unfinished Spring Roll, Wang Huijuan confesses her feelings to her parents. After a short farewell, Wang Huijuan pulled out her packed suitcase from her room and set off for Wuhan.

DISPOSABLE MEDICAL CAPS, disposable inspection gloves, disposable protective clothing, disposable shoe covers, N95 masks, full-size suction protectors, protective face panels, goggles... filled 22 suitcases. Huashan Hospital Wang Huijuan and other four people with 22 boxes of protective supplies and some nervous mood, in the late evening of New Year's Eve boarded the plane to Wuhan.

In the early morning of the first Lunar Year of the rat, the Shanghai medical team plane landed at Wuhan Tianhe Airport. Taking the bus to the hotel, she understood for the first time what the news meant by the closure of the city. "Not a single car, not a single pedestrian, shocked, shocked, " she recalled.

After a short break, on the afternoon of January 25, Wang Huijuan attended a group meeting of the medical team to learn about the prevention and control of pneumonia caused by COVID-19 infection, as well as the disinfection and self protection procedures of the medical staff. Especially when it comes to learning how to put on and off a hazmat suit.

Although she has worked at the INTENSIVE-CARE UNIT FOR YEARS and experienced emergency room visits during the SARS era, it is the first time she has worn off a protective suit. In the afternoon of the same day, the Mount Hua Hospital assisted four people from Hubei Province to wear off their protective clothing four to five times, and mutual supervision pointed out the deficiencies.

On January 26, Wang Huijuan entered Jinyintan hospital to start work. When she actually put on the suit and had to face the real patient, she was a little scared and nervous, and nervous because of the fear of the unknown, and she didn't know what to face next. Before entering the room, the new patient was nothing more than a figure in the news.

I wasn't used to it at first. Strange Ward, strange colleagues, even looking for a needle to ask the hospital nurses. Meanwhile, we have to deal with "difficult" patients.

Not only was there a coma patient in her four-person Ward, there was also a moody patient in Florida. As a result of wearing non-invasive breathing machine will have discomfort, Hu is particularly irritable, constantly pulled off breathing machine mask. As soon as the mask was removed, Hu's Oxygenation dropped to 70 percent, sometimes as low as 50 percent.

Normal Oxygenation is above 94% , and below that, you're not getting enough oxygen. Wang Huijuan found pulled off the hood of the Old Hu lips are purple, immediately pacified, and help the old Hu put on, a day to remove the action to wear repeatedly.

What's more, when he was upset, Hu would make all kinds of demands, one moment to eat candy, the next to eat cookies, the next to wear green clothes and so on. There is no nurse in the ward, Wang Huijuan to assume the care of the work, to meet the requirements of Hu. Ms. Wang, who works eight hours a day during her initial deployment, said she sometimes had to "wrestle" with Hu for eight hours. "every time the Hu people are more awake and say thank you to me, all the tiredness disappears. "

With the completion of the system, procedures gradually standardized, Shanghai medical team shift time was compressed to 4 hours. Although the initial working time is cut in half, it is still a big challenge for Wang Huijuan. In order not to go to the toilet, stand guard, she chose not to eat or drink before work, until the completion of the work.

At the same time, the chest tightness of the protective clothing + mask is one thing that must be overcome every day. For Wang Huijuan, the most comfortable moment of every day is the moment when she takes off the protective clothing.

Work is hard, life must be optimistic. Wang Huijuan has a very full schedule every day, cleaning the room, sleeping and resting, doing Radio calisthenics three times a day, brushing her mobile phone.

On a February afternoon, the Shanghai medical team received a snack from one of Shanghai's leading bakeries. Opening the gift box, she was surprised to find that there is a doll bear inside, a moment "heart melt. ". In addition, a batch of Shanghai specialties such as steak from the Jinjiang Hotel and butterfly cakes from international hotels were fed to the Shanghai medical team one after another.

Spring is here in Wuhan, and Cherry Blossoms are about to bloom in Luojia Shan, as patients leave the hospital in droves. Wang Huijuan is looking forward to a day when she can go back to Shanghai to enjoy the flowers.

4. Bahaguli, medical team publicist: a Xinjiang girl dances for a patient in a shelter

"They say I warm Wuhan, but it's the people of Wuhan who warm me, " said Baha Guli Tolehen, a member of the propaganda committee and liaison for the second group of medical teams supporting Hubei Province in Xinjiang

On Feb. 12, a douyin video went viral, and a paramedic from the Xinjiang medical team performed a Xinjiang dance for patients at a shelter hospital in the living room of Wuhan.

The hospital began admitting patients on February 6. At the beginning, there were many questions about the shelter hospital. Some people thought the condition of the temporary shelter hospital was not good enough, while others thought it was a "large-scale cross-infection site. ". In the early morning hours of Feb. 4, the Second Group of Xinjiang Medical Team to support Hubei arrived in Wuhan. Vice leader Bahaguli, after learning how to put on and off protective clothing, entered the living room shelter hospital in Wuhan on Feb. 11.

The moment she stepped inside, she was shocked by the sight of almost all the patients lying in bed. There was no movement. There was an atmosphere of anxiety, tension and even hopelessness in the shelter.

She went to the center of the Shelter Hospital and picked up the microphone, "I am a Kazakhs aid worker from Xinjiang. We are not afraid to come all the way to Wuhan. So many medical workers from all over the country have come for you. You must cheer up, " he said

Everyone's emotions were somewhat aroused, she added, performing two dances for everyone, a Xinjiang dance, a Kazakh dance, "to watch the main, want to learn I can teach. "

Soon, some people were inspired, "unfortunately, wearing protective clothing, can only try to teach some of the pace. "

Because of the lack of specific drugs, The Adventure of the Resident Patient's greatest need is to strengthen their immune system, in addition to providing them with adequate nutrition, boost their spirits, and maintain a happy mood is also important. With the help of these field support teams, every afternoon, everyone in the shelter hospital is organized to dance and sing together.

When Bahaguli came out of work at the Shelter Hospital, she clicked on her cell phone and found 38 missed calls. She was shocked. She thought she had made a mistake. Her mother also called. Before entering the shelter, she did not tell her family, who thought she was just coming to Wuhan to do some logistics and liaison materials.

Her mother told her that she had seen videos of her dancing in the shelter on the Internet and felt she had never danced so well at home before. "She just kept asking me how I was doing in there, like a journalist, and told me not to drag everyone down. "

Soon, patients began to leave the shelter. One day, a man came out of the shelter after recovering. He kept shouting, "I'm out! So happy! So good! " The enthusiasm of the Wuhan people also infected Bahaguli, wuhan really is a city of heroes, she said.

She found that almost all residents of Wuhan were doing their part to fight the epidemic at any cost. The team members who supported the rescue team did not say "no" to any of their requests, "hotels are trying to give us more nutrition. They don't want to eat or drink, so they save it for us. "

There were fewer and fewer patients in the shelter, from the first 1,000 or so confirmed cases, to 800,300,100. Bahaguli cried when she saw the empty bed. She was both happy and reluctant to part with it. Some of the patients were still in contact with her, cheering each other up. "They say I warmed Wuhan, but it was the people of Wuhan who warmed me. ".

On the afternoon of March 7, she and other medical staff held a small party for female patients in the living room of Wuhan before the patients left to prepare for the rest of the cabin. Medical staff prepared a new set of warm underwear, Xinjiang rescue team also brought home specialties, red dates, walnuts, "are we usually also reluctant to eat. "

5, Isolation Ward nurse Li Hui: wear diapers, also have to insist on

Li Hui, a nurse in the isolation ward of Tianyou Hospital affiliated to Wuhan University of Science and Technology, said, "I ever thought I was going to be a nurse for the rest of my life? But now I feel I have to stick to this task. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Li Hui, a girl born after 1990, was one of the first nurses on duty in the second ward of Tian You hospital affiliated to Wuhan University of Science and Technology. Living here are confirmed new coronary pneumonia patients, working hours to be fully "armed" : Protective clothing, goggles, gloves, shoes, as can not be less.

Li Hui volunteered to work in the second ward and sent her sister back to her parents. She is 15 years old and lives with her. "after all, it is an infectious disease and there is a risk of infection. ". Li Hui did not tell her parents about her new job. She planned to go home for the Spring Festival to reunite with her parents. Instead, she chose to work the night shift. She could take two days off, just enough to go home for the Spring Festival. But I haven't been able to go back to my parents'house since I got to the isolation ward.

At first, though, she and her colleagues often had to work overtime to get the work done. The normal shift was eight hours, and the night shift was nine to eight and eleven hours the next morning. Later, Hospital Management Changed Shifts to six-hour shifts.

One night shift, two people, about 30 or 40 patients. Daily work for patients to do examination, infusion or other treatment care. At first, Li Hui did not know about the new coronavirus very well. She did not expect it to be so contagious. Later, the more she learned, she became a little nervous and scared. But she saw everyone working as usual and talked with her colleagues. Soon she was back to normal.

Every day to work early, the head nurse will help them put on protective clothing, protective clothing, goggles, masks, shoe covers, gloves, fully armed before entering the isolation ward. "If you dress well, you won't be able to do your work smoothly, such as using gloves to inject needles. " Ms. Li said the same work now takes a little longer.

Once in the ward, can not come out for more than 6 hours, also can not go to the bathroom, because once come out or go to the bathroom, means a suit of protective clothing waste, "we are very economical, will control drinking water" .

At first, at the end of the day, my ears hurt and my eyes hurt. After wearing the goggles, the goggles would soon become foggy and foggy. So we began to explore our experience slowly. We tried to scrub the goggles with alcohol, iodophors and hand sanitizer. Later, we found that the hand sanitizer was washed and then dried with toilet paper, goggles can maintain about 4 hours not fuzzy, Li Hui and partners on the first four hours of the important, careful treatment work to finish.

You wear an N95 mask too long, you'll get an earache. They modified the handles of milk crates, hooked them up to two hooks and put them directly behind their heads so their ears didn't hurt. During their menstrual period, they have to wear "diapers" , "more convenient, otherwise, more than 6 hours really difficult. ".

The most intense period is from late January to mid February. Li Works nearly 11 hours a day, then falls asleep and sleeps until the next day. "losing a few pounds is another gain, " Ms. Li said

When she was studying nursing, Li Hui didn't have much love for the profession. She was advised by her family. Sometimes she wondered if she was going to continue as a nurse? But when the epidemic came, she never thought about the problem, "I feel that we should stick to our posts, there is a kind of comfort in my heart, I feel that it is a good thing to help others. ".

Li Hui to the isolation ward work, is her cousin and cousin husband first know, and then sent to the family wechat group, parents know. Li Hui was surprised when his father, who had never sent a video, called the same afternoon, "I kind of knew why he was calling me, " he said. "It took him a while to answer the phone. My Dad said, 'why didn't you tell me you made such a big decision? ' And he said, "I cried. "

Finally, Dad said, "there's always someone to do something, so he supported me, and then he waited for me to come home for the New Year. ". It was the seventh day of the Lunar New Year.

Li Hui thought, after the outbreak ended, if the hospital quarantined patients at that time have not been discharged from the hospital, will definitely choose to continue to work in the isolation ward. After whether to return to the original department or to other departments can rotate to learn, "since can not contribute to the country, then stick to their posts, if you can do a good job in their posts, it is quite good. "
